[{"id":"FT3197","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<p>Additional Cl<sub>2</sub>(<em>g</em>) is injected into the system at equilibrium. Which of the following graphs best shows the rate of the reverse reaction as a function of time? (Assume that the time for injection and mixing of the additional Cl<sub>2</sub>(<em>g</em>) is negligible.)</p>","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<p>Refer to the following.</p>\n\n<p class=\"text-center\">PCl<sub>5</sub>(<em>g</em>) â‡„ PCl<sub>3</sub>(<em>g</em>)+Cl<sub>2</sub>(<em>g</em>)</p>\n\n<p>PCl<sub>5</sub>(<em>g</em>) decomposes into PCl<sub>3</sub>(<em>g</em>) and Cl<sub>2</sub>(<em>g</em>) according to the equation above. A pure sample of PCl<sub>5</sub>(<em>g</em>) is placed in a rigid, evacuated 1.00L container. The initial pressure of the PCl<sub>5</sub>(<em>g</em>) is 1.00 atm. The temperature is held constant until the PCl<sub>5</sub>(<em>g</em>) reaches equilibrium with its decomposition products. The figures below show the initial and equilibrium conditions of the system.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"The figure shows 2 circles representing containers. The left circle is labeled Figure 1: Initial. The interior of Figure 1 is labeled P C L 5, P subscript total equals one point zero zero atmosphere. The right circle is labeled Figure 2: Equilibrium. The interior of Figure 2 is labeled P C L 5 comma P C L 3 comma and C L 2, P subscript total equals one point four zero atmospheres.\" height=\"236\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/9af95166eab9fc7ba980a6d29a8f850b/original.png\" width=\"400\"></p>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<img alt=\"Each option shows a graph with the horizontal axis labeled Time and the vertical axis labeled Reverse Rate. There is a point labeled C L 2 Added about one-third of the way along the horizontal axis.  Option A. A line begins on the horizontal axis at the point labeled C L 2 Added and curves steeply up and to the right. The line appears to level off after about half of the graphed time has elapsed.\" height=\"190\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/b9239a54ac19c53bf245d03b9a3ada4d/original.png\" width=\"200\">","<img alt=\"Option B. A line begins about one-fourth of the way up the vertical axis and moves horizontally to the right. At the point labeled C L 2 Added, the line moves vertically up to the top of the graph area where it then curves gradually down and to the right leveling off above where the line started. The line appears to level off after about half of the graphed time has elapsed.\" height=\"216\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/375c5f9edc5e6f327f99f9b4a8373294/original.png\" width=\"200\">","<img alt=\"Option C. A line begins slightly more than one-half of the way up the vertical axis and moves horizontally to the right. At the point labeled C L 2 Added, the line moves vertically up to slightly below the top of the graph area where it then curves gradually down and to the right leveling off below where the line started. The line appears to level off after about two-thirds of the graphed time has elapsed.\" height=\"203\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/4fd814f0c7bff94cdedd4c1c36320339/original.png\" width=\"200\">","<img alt=\"Option D. A line begins slightly less than one-half of the way up the vertical axis and moves horizontally to the right. At the point labeled C L 2 Added, the line curves gradually up and to the right where it then appears to level off after about half of the graphed time has elapsed.\" height=\"202\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/79124e64315d95531e6f0f12f0bf142b/original.png\" width=\"200\">"],"answer":0}]